to save text to a local file using javascript in the browser (without server-side interaction), you can use the `download` attribute and `blob` api to create a downloadable file. here's an example:

1. create a button element that triggers the saving function when clicked.
2. define a function that creates a new blob object with the text content, sets its type as "text/plain", and adds the download attribute to it.
3. trigger the download attribute on the created link element.

```javascript
const savebtn = document.querySelector("#save-button");
let textcontent; // store the text content in a variable

function savesummary() {
  const summarytext = document.queryselector(".summary").innertext;
  const blob = new blob([summarytext], { type: "text/plain" });
  const link = document.createlink();
  link.href = url.createobjecturl(blob);
  link.download = "summary.txt"; // set the file name and extension
  link.click();
}

savebtn.addeventlistener("click", savesummary);
```

note that this method may not work on all browsers or devices due to security restrictions.
